In `e2e/dev-proxy.e2e.ts` around line 210-221, the test sends SIGTERM to the proxy, waits 500ms, then checks if worker PIDs are still alive using `process.kill(workerPid, 0)`. In Docker (the Playwright base image `mcr.microsoft.com/playwright:v1.58.2-noble`), the 500ms wait is insufficient — the worker process is still alive when checked.

The fix should increase the wait or use a polling loop. A good pattern:

```typescript
// Poll until the worker is dead (up to 5 seconds)
for (const workerPid of workerPids) {
  let alive = true;
  for (let attempt = 0; attempt < 50 && alive; attempt++) {
    try {
      process.kill(workerPid, 0);
      await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 100));
    } catch {
      alive = false;
    }
  }
  expect(alive).toBe(false);
}
```

This replaces the single 500ms wait with a polling loop that checks every 100ms for up to 5 seconds. It passes quickly on fast machines and gives Docker containers enough time.

